<TEXT>
the owner of a multimilliondollar candy 
empire accused of beating people with baseball bats in an effort to 
dominate competition in 30 states pleaded innocent tuesday to 
federal racketeering charges 
us district judge marryanne trump barry said the trial of 
candy giant gerald winters probably would begin in late september 
prosecutors say winters and his associates were responsible for 
a campaign of terror that included alleged beatings with baseball 
bats and metal pipes a kidnapping nine cases of arson three 
shootings and at least a dozen threats against competitors 
nine other people were arrested in the case and are free on 
bail winters is being held without bail because a us magistrate 
earlier ruled the businessman was a menace and dangerous 
winters alleged penchant for violence is in sharp contrast to 
the public portrait he had painted for himself in norwood his 
hometown 
after he established the first liquorfilled chocolate bottle 
factory in the united states venture magazine and the accounting 
firm of arthur young amp co named him entrepreneur of 1987 in the 
new business category 
winters a heavy balding man who was led in and out of court 
wearing shackles on his wrists and ankles sat passively as 
assistant us attorney victor ashrafi told the judge he would 
introduce tape recordings and bank records to prove the 
governments charges 
prosecutors say that winters controlled at least 20 related 
companies some with charitablesounding names the companies 
employed teenagers to go doortodoor but the money from profits 
ended up in winters pockets rather than with any charity 
prosecutors say 
defense attorneys asked barry to delay the case until next 
winter because they need to prepare the case which is expected to 
last three months they intend to call about 100 witnesses 
winters has hired highprofile attorney bruce cutler who has 
successfully defended reputed mob boss john gotti 
outside the court cutler said that he has just taken the case 
and could not comment on the charges he said he would offer the 
court a bail proposal to have winters released at a proceeding 
scheduled for may 29 
</TEXT>
