<TEXT>
only about a quarter of nursing home residents 
with major depression are treated for it chiefly because their 
doctors and nurses do not recognize the condition a study suggests 
its a public health tragedy said study coauthor dr barry 
rovner 
the medical director of a geriatric institution said the finding 
made sense to him but he added that new federal regulations may 
help staff members spot more cases of depression 
rovner an assistant professor of psychiatry at johns hopkins 
university in baltimore presented his results tuesday at the 
annual meeting of the american psychiatric association 
he and colleagues studied 454 patients admitted to eight 
baltimorearea nursing homes in 1987 and 1988 each patient was 
examined by a psychiatrist at two weeks two months and one year 
after admission 
the psychiatrists were looking for major depression which can 
include not only a depressed mood but also markedly diminished 
interest or pleasure in activities of daily life significant 
changes in weight or appetite insomnia or too much sleep 
agitation fatigue feelings of worthlessness or inappropriate 
guilt and recurring thoughts of death or suicide 
in the examinations two weeks after admission they found that 
57 of the 454 patients or 126 percent met the requirements for 
major depression fortyfour of those patients or 78 percent had 
not been treated for the condition at the home 
over the following year 33 new cases of major depression 
developed and 24 were not treated for the condition combining 
both groups only 28 percent of the patients received treatment for 
depresssion rovner said 
the nursing staff doesnt know how to recognize depression and 
the doctors see the patients once a month he said adding that 
doctors often overlook the condition as well the problem is lack 
of training he said 
another problem may be that when a nursing home resident is 
obviously depressed its wrongly attributed to an understandable 
reaction to being in the home he said 
rovner said he believed his results would apply to nursing homes 
in general because demographic characteristics of the patients and 
the homes matched those of national samples 
most of the nursing home residents had been admitted for 
conditions other than depression he said just over 60 percent 
suffered from dementia chiefly alzheimers disease he said 
rovner said he suspects that treating the depression would pay 
off in reduced health care costs depressed nursing home residents 
in his study declined in mental abilities faster than other 
patients and such declines may lead to more costly health care he 
said 
the findings on untreated depression are not surprising said 
dr steven levenson medical director of the levindale geriatric 
center and hospital in baltimore which includes a nursing home a 
geriatric hospital and a rehabilitation center the nursing home 
was not part of rovners study 
its been suspected for some time that depression is a fairly 
significant problem in the institutionalized elderly and that 
it may be missed or confused with dementia or underdiagnosed 
levenson said in a telephone interview 
in contrast to many other health troubles of nursing home 
residents its a treatable and potentially reversible problem 
he said its worth people looking more closely considering more 
carefully 
federal regulations that take effect oct 1 will encourage more 
careful assessments of nursing home residents he said the 
procedure will help staff members who see certain symptoms put 
two and two together and consider depression levenson said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

