exploratory talks between the two governments opened on monday 
after a largely ceremonial opening session the two delegations 
began the first day of substantive discussions today 
at issue are the future of six us military facilities 
including clark air base and subic bay naval base the lease on the 
installations expires in 1991 
the official predicted the negotiations could take a year to 
complete but washington has made clear repeatedly that it has 
severe limits on the amount of financial compensation it can offer 
and is prepared to leave if the cost is too high the official said 
in 1988 the reagan administration pledged 962 million over two 
years to keep the bases through 1991 congress however cut 96 
million from the bush administration aid request for the 
philippines and filipino officials are unhappy with what they view 
as a breach of the agreement 
costs to relocate the facilities elsewhere run between 3 
billion to 4 billion the official said 
there are ways that we could go that have to do with a 
number of facilities that may no longer be required they could 
be turned over to the philippines he said 
the official said the united states was interested in hearing 
all philippine proposals 
while the united states is not interested in adopting a pure 
rentforbases relationship with the philippine government it 
would look more favorably on expanding the commercial relationship 
involving the bases he said 
he cited such examples as opening more of the ship repair 
facility at subic bay to ships other than us naval vessels and 
expanding the commercial use of clark air base to philippines 
airlines 
the official also said the united states was looking at the idea 
of providing the philippine military with equipment that may be 
removed from europe in the event of successful eastwest 
negotiations limiting conventional arms 
in any case the official said the united states is not 
entering the talks with the intention of giving up either clark air 
base or subic bay naval base or swapping one for the other 
its not our position to trade one facility for another 
he said adding at another point wed like to keep both clark 
and subic 
our bottom line is we want to maintain a military 
presence in the philippines the official said if that 
presence is something that we can change the form of and it 
would become more acceptable to the philippines were certainly 
open to change that form 
meanwhile us officials denounced the slayings of two american 
servicemen on sunday outside clark air base 
these despicable acts serve only to strengthen our 
determination to support the filipino people in their desire to 
live in freedom and democracy said state department spokeswoman 
margaret tutwiler 
she said new peoples army communist guerrillas were suspected of 
murdering the men 
this is a case where they are trying to cause us to be so 
fearful that we would back away not only from the bases but also 
from our support for the philippine government the defense 
official said were determined not to let that happen 
asked to assess the stability of the government of philippine 
president corazon aquino the official said the administration is 
worried concerned in light of the attempts to unseat her 
after five coups now its hard to suggest that everything is 
stable and fine in the philippines the official said but he 
noted she was able to survive the multiple overthrow attempts 
which says shes a pretty tough capable leader 
