<TEXT>
college students commit suicide at about half 
the rate of nonstudents their age and suicide rates at highly 
competitive schools are not significantly different from those at 
less rigorous ones an expert says 
allan schwartz chief of the university health services mental 
health section at the university of rochester said students are 
less likely than others their age to kill themselves chiefly 
because they have less access to guns 
he reviewed research monday at the annual meeting of the 
american psychiatric association 
recent data for college students show a suicide rate of six or 
seven per 100000 studentyears he said a studentyear is like a 
manhour 10 studentyears can mean one year for 10 students or 10 
years for one student 
the college rate is about half that for an agematched group 
composed equally of each sex he said 
two lines of evidence suggest that lack of access to guns plays 
the major role he said one is research suggesting that male 
students are only 24 percent as likely to kill themselves with guns 
as male nonstudents are 
the other has to do with the fact that guns are far more popular 
among males who commit suicide than with females who kill 
themselves if lack of access to a gun plays a major role in the 
lower suicide rates in college then the reduction should be 
greater among males than among females schwartz suggested 
that is in fact what research shows with the reduction among 
males about twice that noted for females he said 
whatever the pressures of a rigorous school no link between 
suicide rates and college competitiveness has been observed so far 
suggesting that if one does exist it is only minor schwartz said 
other findings also argue indirectly against any relationship 
he said student suicides peak in september march and january 
which are not the times of most acute academic stress he said 
those are the times of first experiencing separation from home 
or of going home or elsewhere where guns may be more available than 
on campus he said 
dr susan blumenthal a suicide expert at the national institute 
of mental health in rockville md said studies have shown that 
access to firearms does contribute to higher suicide rates 
she agreed that competitiveness of a college does not seem to 
play a role in its suicide rates more important might be 
perfectionism in the student himself which might set him up for 
the humiliating experience that precedes 90 percent of suicides 
she said 
she also stressed that suicides stem from combinations of 
several factors including psychiatic illness such as depression or 
psychosis drug or alcohol abuse personality factors such as 
aggressiveness and impulsivity biological factors such as 
deficiency of the brain chemical serotonin genetic factors and 
environmental factors such as loss of social support from leaving 
behind family and friends to go to school 
these factors can be countered with such things as good 
treatment for psychiatric illness the presence of social support 
such as friends parents and school activities hopefulness and 
good problemsolving skills she said 
</TEXT>
