settled into a slowgrowth lowinflation pace observed john 
connolly an analyst at dean witter reynolds inc that was not 
the consensus conclusion a couple of months ago 
indeed the prevailing fear in the financial world for most of 
early 1990 has been that inflation was accelerating quite 
possibility setting business on a course toward recession 
longterm interest rates as measured by prevailing yields on 
treasury bonds climbed from under 8 percent at the start of the 
year to slightly more than 9 percent four months later 
then the picture was suddenly scrambled by a labor department 
report on may 4 of much slower employment growth in april than had 
been estimated by private analysts on may 11 separate reports 
showed declines in both retail sales and producer prices of 
finished goods 
worried talk about inflation quickly subsided longterm 
interest rates tumbled close to 85 percent and the stock market 
took off 
in the span of just one week the economic outlook has been 
subject to a dramatic turn of events said douglas schindewolf at 
the investment firm smith barney harris upham amp co 
there are hopes that view will be reinforced wednesday with the 
issuance of the consumer price index for april advance estimates 
call for the cpi one of the mostly widely followed gauges of 
inflation to show a rise of perhaps 01 percent or 02 percent 
after much larger increases in the first three months of the year 
even if those expectations are fulfilled it remains to be seen 
whether stock traders will continue to celebrate the new trend but 
bullish observers say there is no arguing with what already has 
happened to stock prices 
a declining and relatively modest inflation rate combined with 
continued economic growth is always bullish for stocks asserted 
analyst stephen leeb in a recent edition of the financial advisory 
letter indicator digest 
leeb maintains that stocks and the economy also are benefiting 
from an increasing rate of savings in this country and from 
shrinking us budget and trade deficits 
the net result is that the united states is becoming more 
productive and more competitive he said 
some other observers arent quite as enthusiastic yet many 
acknowledge that the economic picture looks clearer and brighter 
than it did through the winter and early spring 
but they remain suspicious about conclusions that rest so 
heavily on data covering a very short span of time 
in addition they say what looks today like a smooth soft 
landing for the economy could start worrying the passengers if it 
shows any signs of turning bumpy 
the recovery in stock prices may have further to go say 
analysts at standard amp poors in their publication the outlook 
its too soon to say however that a new leg of the bull market 
is in progress 
