<TEXT>
the signing by the united states and iran of a 
105 million settlement of small claims rising out of the islamic 
revolution removes an irritant in the frayed relations between the 
two nations but leaves larger contested claims unsettled 
and the settlement of some 2300 claims of up to 250000 each 
does not address the major point of friction between tehran and 
washington the continued captivity of six american hostages held 
in lebanon by kidnappers with ties to iran 
state department spokeswoman margaret tutwiler noted monday that 
president bush has said repeatedly that a good place to start the 
normalization of relations would be the release of all american 
hostages 
the settlement which was signed late sunday does clear the way 
for the iranunited states claims tribunal at the hague in the 
netherlands to deal with about 16 billion in major contested 
claims 
negotiations still are under way on about 400000 worth of 
small claims against the united states most of them filed by 
iranian soldiers undergoing training in this country who lost 
possessions when they were ordered expelled after the iranian 
revolution 
a senior us official who briefed reporters on the settlement 
on condition he not be identified noted that irans claims against 
the united states include some 10 billion for military properties 
he said that while the united states believes some of those 
claims have value for others running into the billions of 
dollars our view and the iranian view are far apart 
the settlement of the small claims must now be approved by the 
tribunal which was established under the 1981 algiers accords that 
set the terms for the release of the americans held hostage at the 
us embassy in tehran for 444 days 
once the tribunal approves the 105 million will be paid to the 
united states in one lump sum 
subsequent distribution to a large variety of claimants 
including many americans who lost their personal possessions when 
they fled tehran after the 1979 revolution against the government 
of shah reza pahlavi will be made by the justice departments 
foreign claims settlement commission 
the us official said there is no way to predict how long that 
process might take but experience indicates it could be as long as 
two to four years 
however us officials said payments will be made to claimants 
far faster than if the tribunal were to attempt to deal with them 
case by case 
the state department said that originally 2795 us small 
claims were filed with the tribunal which to date has decided only 
36 of them an additional 72 claims were settled by the parties 
themselves and approved by the tribunal 
the settlement agreement covers 2361 small claims still pending 
at the tribunal ten other claims were dismissed for lack of 
jurisdiction 326 were filed but voluntarily withdrawn and 415 were 
not forwarded by the state department because the filing deadline 
had expired 
under the terms of the settlement us claimants will receive 
about 50 million 
an additional settlement of about 55 million was earmarked to 
repay a loan to iran from the us agency for international 
development 
but officials noted that the terms of the agreements leaves the 
final distribution of the 105 million payment up to the us 
government 
remaining before the tribunal are irans claims arising out of 
the foreign military sales program and claims by us oil companies 
whose property was expropriated 
