the federal election commission dismissed a 
democratic party allegation that a political action committee for 
foreigncar dealers made more than 800000 in illegal donations to 
two republican senate campaigns in 1988 
the commissions lawyers urged the panel to open an enforcement 
action based on the allegations against one of the campaigns that 
of florida sen connie mack but that recommendation was rejected 
by the fecs three republican members quashing the complaint 
macks campaign agreed to pay a 3500 fine to settle a lesser 
allegation that it violated disclosure laws by not listing the 
occupations and addresses of donors in its final preelection 
fundraising reports to the fec 
the agencys decisions on the major allegations in the complaint 
filed by the democratic senatorial campaign committee were made in 
a closed meeting six months ago but they were not made public 
until monday because of the confidential negotiations with the mack 
campaign on the lesser allegation 
the case involved the auto dealers and drivers for free trade 
pac which spent nearly 3 million to influence 1988 congressional 
elections relying heavily on socalled independent expenditures 
the fecs general counsel had urged the commission to accuse the 
auto dealers pac and the mack campaign of violating election laws 
that recommendation said there was reason to believe a 326000 
advertising campaign by the pac supporting mack did not qualify as 
an independent expenditure and therefore was an illegal 
contribution 
but the sixmember commissions three republican appointees 
refused to accept the recommendation four votes are needed for the 
panel to begin an enforcement action 
the commission voted 50 to accept the general counsels 
recommendation that it dismiss the portion of the democratic 
senatorial committees complaint alleging the auto dealers pacs 
521000 effort on behalf of thensen chic hecht rnev was 
coordinated with hechts campaign hecht lost his race with 
democrat richard bryan 
the fec attorneys said that while the pacs ads were similar to 
official campaign ads there was no evidence of coordination 
the democratic committees electioneve complaint alleged the 
spending by the auto dealers pac on behalf of mack was illegal 
because there was coordination between the pac and campaign 
mack was in a close race with democratic rep buddy mckay and 
the committee unsuccessfully sought a preelection ruling from the 
fec ordering the pacs florida advertisements off the air mack 
ultimately won by just 35000 votes of more than 4 million cast 
pacs and other groups are allowed to pay for ads and other 
materials supporting or opposing candidates but such efforts 
qualify as independent expenditures only if there is no contact or 
coordination with the campaigns 
if there is coordination the ads would be considered 
contributions and subject to limits the dealers pac already had 
donated the maximum amounts to mack and hecht before launching the 
advertising campaigns 
in its complaint the democratic committee said the pac and mack 
campaigns both had hired the same advertising firm multimedia 
and a texasbased political consultant karl rove 
in response the dealers pac said it retained multimedia and 
rove for 1988 campaign activities but hired a separate firm for the 
florida ads to avoid any conflicts still the fec general counsel 
said the pac failed to prove there was no coordination and 
recommended that the commission open an enforcement case 
the commissions reasons for rejecting the recommendation were 
unclear the panel traditionally includes in the public record a 
statement explaining its vote but it has yet to do so 
