<TEXT>
the nations top judge today urged congress to 
streamline death penalty appeals so long delays will be eliminated 
the system at present verges on the chaotic chief justice 
william h rehnquist told the american law institute a group of 
lawyers and judges the system cries out for reform 
noting that the average time between sentencing and execution is 
seven or eight years rehnquist said the eight years is 
consumed not by structured review but in fits of frantic action 
followed by periods of inaction he said 
more than 2200 death row inmates across the nation are awaiting 
execution but through the 1980s no more than 25 have been put to 
death in any one year 
rehnquist said congress should change how federal courts review 
capital punishment cases from state courts in ways recommended by a 
committee he appointed two years ago 
that committee headed by retired supreme court justice lewis f 
powell recommended last september that death row inmates be 
limited to one chance to attack their state court sentences in 
state appellate courts and one chance in federal courts 
currently inmates may file several challenges in federal 
courts usually after several unsuccessful appeals in state courts 
the result is that at no point until a death sentence is 
actually carried out can it be said that litigation concerning the 
sentence has run its course rehnquist said in criticizing the 
current system 
the powell committees report was denounced by civil liberties 
lawyers 
rehnquist last october sent the powell committee report directly 
to congress rather than refer it to the us judicial conference 
the federal courts policymaking body which he heads 
fourteen of the judicial conferences 27 members wrote congress 
to request hearings on the conferences recommendations which 
differ significantly from those of the powell committee 
the judicial conferences proposals were hailed by the same 
civil liberties lawyers who had panned the powell committees 
report 
rehnquist today criticized the judicial conferences 
recommendations along with bills introduced by sens joseph biden 
ddel and strom thurmond rsc 
the chief justice said bidens proposal would actually 
exacerbate the delays and repetitiousness of the present system 
he said thurmonds proposal which would eliminate most federal 
court review of death penalty cases is not yet needed 
while this approach might commend itself some years hence it 
does not do so at the present time rehnquist said 
</TEXT>
