<TEXT>
nasa technicians today removed a 
faulty valve that forced the agency to delay the launch of the 
space shuttle columbia from this week to the end of may or 
beginning of june 
a filter on the valve was torn allowing debris to enter 
columbias cooling system said lisa malone spokeswoman for the 
national aeronautics and space administration 
were pretty glad we did find the problem malone said 
now well be on the right track of putting everything back 
together 
columbia had been scheduled to lift off wednesday or thursday 
with seven astronauts and the 100 million astro observatory 
capable of examining sources of ultraviolet and xray radiation 
last week however engineers spotted a problem with the valve 
and nasa postponed the mission two to three weeks 
technicians working on a makeshift platform in columbias 
payload bay about 10 feet above the covered observatory began 
draining toxic freon refrigerant from the shuttles cooling system 
friday they completed the work late monday then cut out the 
valve about the length of a hand and some attached plumbing 
it was the first time such a procedure had ever been performed 
at the launch pad 
replacing the bad valve is expected to take nearly three days 
malone said the cooling system then will be refilled with freon 
and the entire system will be tested 
nasa is expected to set a new launch date early next week 
columbias nine to 10day flight will be the first spacelab 
mission since 1985 and the 36th shuttle mission 
the faulty valve was sent to a nearby rockwell international 
service center for analysis rockwell built columbia and the other 
shuttles 
