chancellor helmut kohl has found that the 
road to german unification is paved with obstacles and marred by an 
occasional pothole 
the latest trouble is a state elections setback that pushed kohl 
to suggest joint german voting a year earlier than planned to 
regain his partys momentum 
kohl and his coalition allies agreed today that elections for a 
united german government should occur as soon as possible that 
brought immediate criticism from the opposition social democrats 
the chancellor conceded a bitter defeat in sundays 
elections in two west german states the social democrats defeated 
his conservative christian democratic party and won control of the 
upper house of parliament the bundesrat 
the social democrats have opposed kohls plans for a quick 
unification proposing a more cautious approach 
hans klein the chief government spokesman said today that all 
sides were unanimously agreed there should be allgerman elections 
at the earliest possible date 
he was not more specific but alfred dregger parliamentary 
leader of kohls christian democrats said he favors either 
replacing the dec 2 federal elections with allgerman ones or 
holding the allgerman vote when the current legislative period 
ends jan 13 1991 
finance minister theodor waigel said he believes an allgerman 
vote will occur this year 
the lower house the bundestag is the actual lawmaking body 
but bundesrat approval is needed for legislation that has direct 
consequences for the finances of west germanys 11 states 
kohls defeat was just one of a growing list of obstacles that 
are plaguing kohls ambitious plans for a rapid unification these 
include 
moscows flat refusal to budge from its position that a united 
germany may not belong to the nato alliance 
polands call for a formal guarantee that a united germany 
will have no claims to its western border 
the threat by east germanys social democrats to pull out of 
the government if unification does not provide strong social 
benefits 
the strong disagreement between east germans and west germans 
over how much property west germans will be able to buy in east 
germany 
that disagreement also reflects east germanys strong fear of 
economic domination by the larger and economically more powerful 
west germany 
the whole thing is going to quickly and just hasnt been 
thought through said one woman during a demonstration of 
shopkeepers monday in east berlin 
east german tenants are banding together to fight what they 
predict will be skyrocketing rents as a result of unification 
others fear the evergrowing number of west germans coming back 
to claim property they abandoned while fleeing the communists after 
world war ii 
east german women are demanding a retention of their nations 
liberal abortion law rather than west germanys more restrictive 
regulations 
in west germany anxious citizens are worriedly pointing to the 
astronomical costs of unification that could run into hundreds of 
billions of dollars 
they are also concerned over predictions of high inflation 
similar to the huge price increases that preceeded the nazi era 
west german voters took their dissatisfaction to the ballot box 
on sunday leading to a resounding defeat for kohls christian 
democrats 
