would have to cut back sharply because of slow sales that in 
turn would produce further job losses 
indeed richard w rahn chief economist with the us chamber 
of commerce said the weak 01 percent growth in industrial 
production in the last 12 months has been accompanied by a loss of 
280000 factory jobs 
output at factories producing both durable and nondurable goods 
fell 06 percent in april durable manufacturing was off a full 10 
percent while nondurable output slipped 01 percent 
mining production however rose 09 percent while utility 
output gained 06 percent 
the fed said its industrial production index in april stood at 
1087 percent of its 1987 base down from 1091 percent in march 
the fed also reported the operating rate of the nations 
factories mines and utilities which usually move in tandem with 
industrial production dipped 05 percentage point to 830 percent 
in april the operating rate measures not only output but also 
changes in productivity levels 
the overall manufacturing operating rate fell 07 points to 822 
percent the rate at factories producing durable goods fell a full 
percentage point to 807 percent while the rate at plants making 
nondurable goods slipped from 846 percent in march to 843 
percent last month 
the operating rate at mines rose 09 points to 883 percent 
while it jumped 05 points to 866 percent at utilities 
