<TEXT>
as white house deficit negotiations got under 
way tuesday a brookings institution report disputed president 
bushs inaugural speech assertion that the nation has more will 
than wallet 
whats lacking it said is not wealth but leadership 
the question is not whether america has enough wallet but 
whether it has the will to use its abundant wealth to solve the 
problems that it faces wrote henry aaron a senior economist 
with the liberal research organization 
the country has plenty of wealth the report said 
the united states is a nation blessed with the highest per 
capita income its national product is 2 times larger than that of 
the secondlargest economy the report said it is enjoying its 
longest peacetime expansion 
facing no military threat or economic crisis the united states 
can muddle through without absolute decline aaron said 
yet americans cannot escape the reality that decisions taken 
during this decade will determine whether the chronicle of growth 
at home and influence abroad continues or flags he said 
the report setting national priorities by nine brookings 
researchers is intended to take a centrist stance toward 
problems on the budget foreign policy defense trade global 
warming education health care and political paralysis 
it was a coincidence that the booksize report came out the day 
talks were opening between bush and congressional leaders on ways 
to take as much as 100 billion out of the projected deficit 
bush who said on inauguration day that the united states cannot 
solve all the worlds problems because we have more will than 
wallet has consistently opposed a tax increase to reduce the 
deficit 
but a tax increase could emerge from the budget talks even 
though both parties have shied away from advocating one the talks 
are expected to last for weeks and could drag on throughout the 
summer 
writing about the political impasse that has made deficit 
reduction difficult political scientist thomas e mann said the 
most striking and unsettling feature of american politics is 
the stark contrast betweeen the extraordinary pace and scope of 
change occurring outside the country and the political immobilism 
within 
mann said bush was unlikely to adopt daring solutions to the 
nations economic problems and was almost sure to prefer to stick 
with a political strategy that barring a deep recession is very 
likely to lead to his reelection in 1992 
but mann argued by accepting a modest increase in taxes 
weighted toward those highincome households that reaped most of 
the economic benefits of the 1980s the president could help the 
country and enhance his own reelection prospects 
such a course he said would eliminate the deficit lower 
interest rates increase investment fuel economic growth and not 
incidentally neutralize efforts by the democrats to mount a 
populist critique of the gop 
these presidential initiatives could break the policy logjam 
help the country begin to deal with its longterm challenges and 
put the republican party in a position to increase its strength at 
all levels of elective office he said 
he said however that it was doubtful that either party would 
adopt unconventional strategies to deal with the nations problems 
aaron labled the problem a psychosis of poverty and 
helplessness 
he blamed it on an extended consumption binge arising from 
the countrys refusal to save more and to cut both personal and 
government spending or to tax itself enough to scale down the 
deficit 
depressed saving slows growth of worker productivity he 
said it is conventional wisdom that because of the deficit the 
united states cannot afford to solve serious problems of health 
care education and infrastructure 
in fact failure to attack these problems and the deficit 
simultaneously stems from a deeper common source american leaders 
have been unwilling or unable to try to persuade the people of the 
need to cut spending to raise taxes or to take other controversial 
actions 
in a proposal to convert the deficit into a modest surplus by 
1995 economist charles l schultze raised the possibility of 
cutting or taxing social security benefits raising taxes by 1 
percent of the national income cutting spending on such middle 
class subsidies as the farm program school lunches for middle 
class children disability compensation to veterans with low 
disability ratings and subsidies for merchant vessels 
he also raised the possibility of imposing user fees for grazing 
on federal lands and raising interest rates for rural 
electrification loans 
that the nation can muddle through sustaining large budget 
deficits without a cyclical crisis does not mean that deficits do 
no harm and can be ignored schultze wrote a successful 
economy ought not only to avoid recession and inflation but also 
to provide for future growth 
</TEXT>
