<TEXT>
psychiatrists and psychologists who viewed old 
home movies usually were able to identify children who would be 
diagnosed with schizophreia as adults a researcher says 
the study supports the view that the disease follows an early 
brain abnormality said psychology professor elaine walker of emory 
university in atlanta 
there may be early subtle signs of vulnerability to 
schizophrenia walker said monday 
the project involved home movies that portrayed five infants and 
children up to age 5 who were later diagnosed with schizophrenia as 
young adults thirteen psychologists and psychiatrists were shown 
the films which also included at least one sibling 
the mental health professionals were asked to guess which one 
later was diagnosed as schizophrenic 
their performance was much better than one would expect by 
chance which suggests they were able to spot clues walker said 
the observers said the signs included delayed development of 
motor skills awkwardness and unexpected emotional responses shown 
in the face 
now researchers plan to analyze the movies with objective 
measures of motor development and facial expression to see if those 
factors tend to identify preschizophrenic children walker said 
walker presented her results at the annual meeting of the 
american psychiatric association the study has been accepted for 
publication in a scientific journal she said 
the clues the raters spotted were amazingly predictive dr 
stephen oxley of duke university in durham nc said after 
walkers presentation 
while the results are very preliminary they suggest there may 
be ways to spot children at risk for developing the disease he 
said 
other research also has pointed to possible early brain 
disturbances in schizophrenia he said 
if children at risk can be spotted early perhaps steps can be 
taken to prevent the disease he said further research also might 
give clues about what part of the brain is involved which might 
guide research into treatment he said 
schizophrenia is marked by a loss of touch with reality called 
psychosis and hallucinations delusions disordered thinking and 
inappropriate emotions 
