<TEXT>
a federal judge tuesday declared 
unconstitutional mandatory drug testing for attorneys applying for 
jobs in the justice departments antitrust division 
the ruling by us district court judge gerhard gesell came in 
the case of carl willner who filed suit after the justice 
department tentatively accepted him for employment and then asked 
him to submit to a urine test 
gesell said testing willner would infringe on the right of any 
citizen not to be searched without a reasonable basis of suspicion 
the antitrust division requirement offends the fourth 
amendment gesell said 
the case is the first major federal decision on applicant drug 
testing involving government agencies said arthur spitzer an 
attorney for the american civil liberties union who argued on 
behalf of willner 
a onetime mandatory preemployment drug test is required of all 
attorneys accepted for positions in the justice departments 
offices boards and divisions component which includes the 
antitrust division 
gesell pointed out that willner would not have access to top 
secret classified information and was not a prosecutor in drug 
cases the us court of appeals has upheld random testing for 
existing employees in the department in those sensitive positions 
but the appeals court has rejected the departments plan to 
require drug tests for all criminal prosecutors and all employees 
with access to grand jury materials 
the judge said in essence that applicants ought to be treated 
the same as existing employees 
in the willner case the justice department had argued that the 
expectation of privacy is less for an applicant than for an 
existing employee singled out for random testing 
the judge enjoined the department from requiring preemployment 
drug testing for antitrust division applicants if there are no 
grounds for suspicion 
just as a beautiful sand dune crumbles if continuously eroded 
by ocean waves said gesell so will this essential precious 
right become a victim if it is modified at times of stress 
the judge said applicants who would be exposed to top secret 
information could be tested 
gesell said willner lacks standing to challenge all 
preemployment drug testing for the entire department or for the 
entire offices boards and divisions component 
in court arguments april 24 justice department lawyer peter 
robbins pointed out that the applicant test is a onetime event 
you dont want somebody enforcing the law turning around and 
violating the law robbins said 
gesells decision would cut severely into the governments 
ability to conduct widespread applicant testing said spitzer 
spitzer said willner now in private practice in washington is 
scheduled to start his justice department job in july 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

