do business with south africa to protest its apartheid laws 
requiring racial separation 
wilder ordered no new investments in the companies and said 
state agencies and institutions should begin divesting from 
companies with substantive interests in the country 
since he announced the plan saturday during a commencement 
address at norfolk state university he has been praised by blacks 
but criticized by conservatives who had been pleased with his tight 
fiscal policies 
im very pleased hes taking this step i would hope and 
expect more progressive actions said charles e jones an old 
dominion university associate professor who had joined other black 
scholars in criticizing wilders new mainstream conservativism 
it could be a costly process depending on how they handle 
it said state sen hunter b andrews a conservative democrat 
who has frequently tangled with the democratic governor 
wilders order affects nearly 1 billion in state investments 
primarily by the state employees pension fund and several colleges 
and universities 
the governor said he would like to see divestiture completed 
before his term ends in january 1994 
he insisted that virginia would not face the same problems as 
other states such as new jersey which lost as much as a 500 
million by divesting 42 billion in south africanlinked holdings 
in three years 
ours will be prudent and i can say to you that i wouldnt 
necessarily mirror the example of new jersey with reference to how 
they went about handling that matter he said 
wilder said he set the south african policy because university 
board members had asked his administration what they should do 
about such investments 
he said its a valid question whether the state should 
divest from companies doing business in other countries that 
violate human rights such as south korea but that south africas 
system is more oppressive than other nations 
</TEXT>
