<TEXT>
hardline communist borisav jovic of 
serbia took over tuesday as head of yugoslavias collective 
presidency and denounced democratic reforms in two of the nations 
republics 
the nation is wrapped in political and ethnic tensions and 
jovic said in his inaugural speech that the crisis had brought 
yugoslavia to the brink of civil war and its breakup 
he appeared to make conflicting statements about the emerging 
westernstyle democracies in croatia and slovenia criticizing 
efforts to abandon socialism but also supporting laws for secession 
jovic took over as leader of the eightmember presidency from 
janez drnovsek a slovene 
each of the countrys six republics and two provinces has a 
representative on the presidency who holds the top post for one 
year on a rotating basis 
yugoslavias founder josip broz tito designed the system in 
what was seen as an attempt to guard against a power struggle in 
this ethnically mixed country after his death 
the presidency is formally yugoslavias highest governing body 
and is in charge of the armed forces 
yugoslavias communist party continues to rule in principle on 
the federal level but it has been crippled since january when 
slovenian and croatian members walked out of a national meeting 
accusing the serbians of seeking domination 
slovenia and croatia later held the first free elections in 
yugoslavia in 50 years centerright parties won to the 
displeasure of the serbian communists who still advocate their 
partys monopoly of power 
it is evident that there are forces which under the cloak of 
democratic changes are trying to achieve their strategic goal of 
abandoning the socialist orientation of our country even at the 
price of its breakup jovic said in his inaugural address we 
will resolutely oppose this 
however he added that he would work for laws that would permit 
peaceful secession of individual states 
jovic 62 is considered an ally of serbias communist 
president slobodan milosevic who also opposes multiparty 
democracy in yugoslavia 
both support yugoslavias federal system with strong central 
authority but that system has been seriously weakened since the 
free elections in slovenia and croatia 
those republics are demanding that yugoslavia transform itself 
into a loose confederation 
the political conflict is intensifying the deep ethnic rivalries 
that have existed since the country was united in 1918 
the most serious ethnic conflict is in kosovo a province that 
is part of serbia ethnic albanians make up 90 percent of the 
provinces population and the region enjoyed broad autonomy until 
changes last year that gave serbia control of the police judiciary 
and education 
serbian authorities say the changes were necessary to protec the 
provinces serbian minority from harassment 
