<TEXT>
a company has agreed to pay 35 million 
in back pay to women employees in what labor secretary elizabeth 
dole on tuesday called one of the largest equalemployment 
opportunity settlements in us history 
precision castparts corp of portland will pay about 1000 women 
who were steered into traditionally female jobs when they were 
hired the labor department said in announcing the settlement 
tuesday 
the money will be paid to women who worked in hourly 
nonclerical jobs at the companys plants in portland at any time 
from 1978 through 1988 according to roy marvin the companys vice 
president of administration 
precision castparts which manufactures jet engine parts and 
other metal components for the aerospace industry will send 
notices to women eligible for benefits within 45 days marvin said 
women who do not receive notices within 45 days and who believe 
they are eligible should contact the department of labor he said 
the settlement is the result of a compliance review conducted by 
the labor departments office of federal contract compliance 
programs after a complaint was filed in march 1987 
the complaint alleged that the company had violated an executive 
order that prohibits federal contractors from discriminating on the 
basis of race sex religion color or national origin the order 
also requires contractors to take affirmative action measures in 
hiring women and minorities 
women represent an important and growing part of todays labor 
force dole said in a prepared statement if america is to 
remain competitive it is no longer just an option for companies to 
employ and promote qualified women and minorities into 
nontraditional jobs it is a business and legal necessity 
this settlement is one of the largest equal opportunity 
agreements in labor department history and further demonstrates the 
departments commitment to eliminating discrimination in the 
workplace 
as part of the settlement the company agreed to provide more 
opportunities for women to transfer to higherpaying jobs within 
the company 
the labor department said its investigation revealed that 
precision castparts ushered women into traditionally female jobs 
that were lowerpaying and provided less opportunity to compete or 
train for higherpaying jobs which traditionally have been filled 
by men at the three plants 
the company said it was denying the allegations but decided to 
negotiate a settlement anyway 
precision said in a news release that it has taken steps to 
increase the percentage of women in its bluecollar workforce and 
in traditional male jobs in particular 
our efforts to increase opportunities for women are already 
showing results marvin said the number of women in 
bluecollar jobs has doubled since 1980 a period when our overall 
employment levels have increased dramatically in percentage terms 
women are now 33 percent of the bluecollar workforce compared to 
26 percent in 1980 
