<TEXT>
fifteen years of unleaded gas in the 
tank is helping clean up more than smoggy city air dramatic lead 
decreases also have been reported in forest soil far from urban 
areas 
scientists had feared that toxic lead emissions wafting from 
vehicle tail pipes threatened trees and other forest life but a 
recent study credits the clean air act with bringing relatively 
speedy relief 
its beautiful the curve showing the decline of lead said 
thomas g siccama a forest ecologist at the yale university school 
of forestry and environmental studies 
it has left the forest floor faster than the general community 
of ecologists thought he said 
in 1980 siccama and two other scientists william h smith of 
yale and donald l mader of the university of massachusetts 
documented that lead levels in massachusetts forest soil had jumped 
significantly between 1962 and 1978 
the amount of lead per square meter had increased from 682 
milligrams to 1160 
siccama smith and others including andrew j friedland of 
dartmouth college and arthur h johnson of the university of 
pennsylvania began looking more closely at forest surface soil 
typically a mat of organic matter 2 to 4 inches deep 
they took samples in forests extending from pennsylvania through 
new hampshire 
over the past year they and other researchers reviewed the 
data their work has not yet been published but siccama said clear 
trends were apparent 
at a cathedral pines forest test site near cornwall conn yale 
graduate student julie tritschler found lead had fallen 26 percent 
since 1980 down from 1275 milligrams per square meter to 940 
at hubbard brook in west thornton nh lead levels in 1975 
were approaching 1100 milligrams per square meter by 1988 they 
had fallen to under 800 milligrams per square meter siccama said 
michael j kellett northeast regional director for the 
wilderness society was encouraged by the lead decreases but 
cautioned that it is important to learn where the lead is going 
because it might end up in underground water supplies 
siccama and others say the decline in soil lead levels is almost 
certainly because of mandated unleaded gasoline use in new cars 
that began in 1975 
that was the whole point of the law siccama said it is a 
oneonone connection we know it has gone down in the rain and 
weve followed it going down in the soil where we knew it was 
accumulating 
</TEXT>
