<TEXT>
the chief justice of the united states called 
on congress tuesday to limit death penalty defendants to just two 
appeals one in their state court and one in the federal system 
there is no limit to such appeals now and generally each case 
sees several appeals filed in each court system 
as a result chief justice william h rehnquist said in an 
address to the american law institute the result is that at no 
point until a death sentence is actually carried out can it be said 
that litigation concerning the sentence has run its course the 
system at present verges on the chaotic 
a committee appointed by rehnquist last fall headed by retired 
supreme court justice lewis f powell recommended the twoappeal 
limit rehnquist sent the report directly to congress bypassing 
the us judicial conference the policymaking body for the 
federal courts he heads 
fourteen of the 27 members of the conference wrote congress to 
request hearings on the conferences recommendations which differ 
significantly from those of the powell committee 
civil liberties lawyers generally criticized the powell 
committee recommendations 
there are now more than 2200 prisoners under sentence of death 
around the united states during the 1980s there have been at most 
25 executions a year 
noting that the average time between sentencing and execution is 
seven or eight years rehnquist said the eight years is 
consumed not by structured review but in fits of frantic action 
followed by periods of inaction 
