this sunday the stillgrowing cable industry 
will gather in atlanta home of ted turner and cnn to start the 
national cable television associations annual fourday convention 
but hovering over the usual convention exhibits panel 
discussions dealmaking and whoopee will be the specter of a 
possible return to federal regulation that cable systems largely 
shucked six years ago 
its a big concern for the industry says ncta president james 
p mooney one he thinks may not be fully warranted 
if there is action by congress or the federal communications 
commission he says increasingly im convinced that it will be 
modest in scope 
cable operators may particularly worry about a return to 
regulations giving cities power over the rates cable systems charge 
customers mooney says but he says he doubts either congress or 
the fcc will do anything that would hamper the continued growth of 
cable 
and says thomas s rogers president of nbc cable and business 
development its a good bet there wont be any bill enacted this 
year despite more than a dozen reregulation proposals pending in 
congress 
once just a means of getting a clear broadcast signal into 
homes cable now also is a programming giant and a collective rival 
of nbc abc and cbs nbc and abc themselves are active in cable 
notably nbcs new cnbc channel and abcs 80 percent ownership of 
the espn sports channel 
once a minor player on the tv scene cable now is in nearly 58 
percent of the nations 921 million homes with televisions 
according to nielsen estimates 
but with its growth has come criticism that includes consumer 
complaints to congress over increases that have occurred in cable 
rates since cable was broadly deregulated and cable systems 
generally allowed to set their own rates 
the ncta contends the worst is over 
mooney agrees noting that a general accounting office study 
shows that in the two years after deregulation began basic cable 
rates rose 29 percent and the overall customer bill went up 14 
percent 
but in the 14 years before deregulation cable rates lagged far 
behind the us consumer price index he says and cable wasnt 
allowed to develop as a programming medium because we didnt have 
the money to do it 
it has that now but consumer grumbles continue according to a 
wall street journalnbc poll in march it found that 62 percent of 
those surveyed generally like what their cable systems offer 
but 37 percent it said are dissatisfied with cables cost and 
question whether the rates are reasonable the survey of 1003 
registered voters had a 3 percent margin of error nbc says 
the rate issue provokes much of the capitol hill action yet 
its an enormously difficult one for congress to confront 
particularly given the policy reversal that it represents says 
nbcs rogers 
he refers to the 1984 cable deregulation act he helped draft as 
a staff member of a house telecommunications subcommittee 
two reports expected soon in washington may have some impact on 
the legislative front one due in july from the fcc concerns the 
state of the cable industry today and what if any changes are 
needed 
the other to come at the end of june from the gao is an update 
on cable rate increases 
what cable offers today is lightyears from what it was five 
years ago says kay koplovitz president of the usa network 
which says it serves 53 million homes now the question is can 
it stabilize without regulation and will it stabilize without 
regulation 
