<TEXT>
peace talks aimed at ending nearly three 
decades of war between eritrean rebels and the ethiopian government 
are stalled and unlikely to resume 
preliminary discussions with former president jimmy carter as 
chairman began in atlanta last september and moved to nairobi the 
capital of kenya two months later 
negotiations in nairobi ended with the government and rebel 
delegations clearly at odds but agreeing to continue talks under 
the joint mediation of carter and julius nyerere former president 
of tanzania 
a third round was tentatively scheduled for early march in 
nairobi but foundered on a dispute over whether the united nations 
should send an observer 
eritrean rebels see un participation as de facto recognition 
of their movement which controls 80 percent of the eritrean 
countryside president mengistu haile mariams government opposes 
it for the same reason 
carter invited the united nations to take part on behalf of the 
rebels and said his offer was rejected 
rebel leaders said the invitation should have been sent jointly 
by them and the representatives of mengistus government and 
accused carter of doubledealing which the former president denied 
the issue will ultimately go to the united nations ali 
sayed abdalla foreign minister of the eritrean peoples liberation 
front said in an interview the un must guarantee any accord 
so why not agree to have it represented as an observer at the peace 
talks 
a western diplomat in addis ababa ethiopias capital said i 
see absolutely no chance for a resumption the military situation 
has changed radically since september and the government seems to 
be reeling i suspect the eplf feels it can stand pat on its 
demands 
