<TEXT>
pope john paul ii watched with satisfaction 
as the democratic spirit triumphed over communism in eastern europe 
but the winds of change that swept the world which the pontiff 
so encouraged have made some roman catholics wonder when the 
revolution will touch their own church 
john paul for his part wonders what the winds blowing from the 
west hold for his newly liberated flock in the east it is a moment 
of great joy for the church and also poses new challenges 
critics like the rev hans kung the swiss theologian punished 
for his liberal views have said the triumph of prodemocracy 
movements in eastern europe left the vatican as a last bastion of 
totalitarianism 
several liberal catholic groups in the united states have drawn 
up a statement urging the pope to share his power the call to 
reform was signed by one bishop and some prominent theologians 
nuns and priests 
calls for drastic change are nothing new in the papacy of john 
paul a native of poland where open catholic dissent in the long 
communist era was unthinkable 
during a historic visit last month the pope hailed the strength 
of the faith in czechoslovakia which he said was deepened and 
purified by lengthy suffering he also warned of dangers 
inherent in renewed contacts with the west 
unfortunately not everything the west proposes as a 
theoretical vision or as a concrete life practice reflects gospel 
values john paul told his bishops he urged them to prepare 
immunizing defenses against such western viruses as 
secularism and hedonistic consumerism 
john paul who was 70 on may 18 is in the 11th year of his 
papacy and vatican insiders believe those hoping for radical 
reforms will be disappointed 
i dont feel such changes will happen under this pope a 
senior vatican official said invoking the usual ground rule of 
anonymity 
for example the congregation for the doctrine of the faith the 
guardian of doctrinal orthodoxy is preparing a document on the 
churchs moral teaching expected to be an answer to criticism from 
theologians 
much of such criticism has come in the past year from 
theologians in western europe concerned about the church ban on 
contraception and the popes exercise of power particularly his 
choice of bishops 
for the pope and vatican there is no contradiction in seeking 
democracy in civil society while not applying it to the church 
on his flight to the united states in 1987 a reporter told john 
paul some american catholics felt the church was not democratic 
enough 
the catholic church is not a democratic institution he 
replied it is an institution governed by jesus christ a 
theocratic one 
while the imperial trappings of the papacy have been removed 
popes are installed now not crowned john paul reminded 
brazilian bishops earlier this year that power in the church comes 
from above not below 
to the pope christian teaching has been entrusted to the church 
by christ to be accepted in its entirety he has said repeatedly 
that people who accept only what they want cannot consider 
themselves good catholics 
john paul is not responsible for the teachings most frequently 
criticized the ban on artificial birth control and divorce 
mandatory priestly celibacy and the prohibition on women in the 
priesthood but he has not tolerated dissent or doubts about them 
for him the reforms of the second vatican council in the 1960s 
were the churchs revolution and now it is a matter of containing 
their excesses 
kung who has questioned papal infallibility the celibacy rule 
and other church teachings was stripped of his right to teach as 
an official catholic theologian in december 1979 little more than 
a year into john pauls reign pope paul vi who died in 1978 had 
merely warned kung 
in an interview with the swiss newspaper basler zeitung in 
december kung said the last diehards sit today in the vatican 
the last ones who have not yet realized that the world no longer 
tolerates authoritarian and totalitarian systems 
the new us statement published in march as an advertisement 
in the new york times said the church was crippled by its 
failure to address fundamental justice issues within its own 
structures among the signatories was emerson moore an auxiliary 
bishop in the new york archdiocese 
these are the voices from the west an important question for 
the pope is whether there will be voices of dissent from the east 
now that the churchs long trial under communism is over 
moving quickly to keep pace with the political changes john 
paul while in czechoslovakia called bishops from eastern and 
western europe to an unprecedented synod to be held next year 
</TEXT>
