<TEXT>
womans day one of the seven major womens 
service magazines is being put up for sale so hachette sas us 
publishing business can trim its debt and concentrate on magazines 
with international potential 
the proposed sale comes amid sluggishness bordering on recession 
in the advertising environment for magazines that has been keenly 
felt at womans day the nations 10th largest magazine by 
circulation last year 
industry analysts said hachettes decision to abandon the 
fiercely competitive womens service segment illustrates the 
difficulty facing a company that owns only one title in competing 
against companies that each own two titles in the same category 
the new york times co hearst corp and meredith corp each own 
two of the socalled seven sisters publications 
hachettes diamandis communications inc said monday it has 
hired the investment banker veronis suhler amp associates inc to 
conduct an auction for womans day over the next several weeks 
circulation at womans day fell 155 percent to 47 million last 
year according to the audit bureau of circulations that knocked 
it to sixth from third place among the seven sisters leading only 
redbook at 39 million 
advertising pages were down at four of the seven magazines in 
the first quarter of the year with womans day suffering the 
deepest drop at 221 percent that was followed by a 191 percent 
decline at family circle according to publishers information 
bureau 
the decision to sell womans day which was founded in 1937 and 
is sold mainly at the supermarket checkout counter marks an abrupt 
reversal for hachette 
a year ago diamandis communications was reported to have been 
close to an agreement to purchase mccalls magazine another 
leading womens service magazine 
but mccalls was sold instead for a reported more than 80 
million to the new york times co which also publishes family 
circle 
hearst owns redbook and good housekeeping while meredith owns 
ladies home journal and better homes amp gardens 
hachette was finding it hard to compete on a standalone 
basis said peter appert who follows the media industry for cj 
lawrence morgan grenfell 
he said the other owners were able to attract advertisers by 
offering them package deals in both of their magazines in doing 
so he said owners of two magazines can often get more ad revenue 
overall than if the magazines were sold separately to advertisers 
richard kostyra who oversees evaluation of media for the ad 
agency j walter thompson said the womens service magazine field 
is one of the most competitive categories for attracting 
advertising 
these magazines are oftentimes viewed interchangably there is 
tremendous pressure on publishers to compete by offering ad rate 
discounts or other deals to advertisers he said 
early speculation about who might be interested in womans day 
included each of the current owners of womens magazines and bauer 
publishing co lp the german company that brought out first for 
women magazine last year 
in announcing the proposed sale peter diamandis president and 
chief executive of diamandis communications said the company wants 
to concentrate on creating or buying special interest magazines 
with an international appeal 
the company already publishes 18 special interest magazines 
including road amp track popular photography and boating it also 
publishes the fashion magazine elle which is published in 17 
countries 
didier guerin president of hachette publishing inc which 
oversees diamandis communications said womans day was not a good 
candidate for international expansion 
he said the magazine is very american because of the way it is 
sold supermarket checkout sales are not popular outside the 
united states he said 
