<TEXT>
manufacturing employment may be on the decline 
nationwide but business leaders in illinois are struggling to 
attract people to highly skilled wellpaying jobs in the precision 
metalworking and plastics industries 
state business and government leaders launched a campaign monday 
to attract workers into the industries which need to fill an 
estimated 24000 jobs in illinois over the next five years 
businessmen say a shortage of young entrants to the labor 
market a lack of knowledge about the field and a stigma against 
manufacturing work are hampering efforts to fill the jobs 
the industry has had a chronic problem for many years in being 
able to attract and train skilled metal workers right now were 
finding the shortage is getting even more severe said bruce 
braker executive vice president of the chicagoarea tooling amp 
manufacturing association 
there simply are fewer young people coming into the labor 
market he explained the baby boomers are working right now 
weve got the birth dearth 
association members were joined monday by gov james r 
thompson who outlined a statewide effort to help the group attract 
and train the new workers 
of the estimated 24000 openings 8000 would be for skilled 
precision metalworkers and 16000 for machine tool setup and 
operating positions 
toolanddie makers and machinists create the tooling that 
makes possible mass production of products ranging from computers 
and satellites to automobiles and appliances thompson said in a 
statement 
the states departments of commerce and community affairs 
employment security and the board of education along with the 
mayors office of economic development will work with the 
association to recruit high school graduates and displaced workers 
into training programs operated by the association and community 
colleges 
precision metalworking jobs pay apprentices 15000 to 20000 a 
year and 25000 to 55000 with overtime for trained workers 
the work involves fabricating parts that fit precisely 
sometimes as accurately as within a micron or 40millionth of an 
inch braker explained 
braker said the group has created a special foundation to fund 
recruitment and training efforts he said between 1000 and 2000 
new workers are needed each year just to maintain overall 
employment but so far the group is graduating only about 200 
workers a year from its training program 
you cant become a toolanddie maker unless you can work with 
trigonometry and can read at the 11th or 12thgrade level he 
said 
precision metalworking has been primarily a white male industry 
braker said so the industry must seek to attract more females and 
minorities 
one problem he said is that upwardly mobile young people 
white and black usually want to go to college rather than into 
manufacturing 
theres a generally negative perception of working in 
manufacturing or with your hands braker said 
many young people think of a factory as a traditionally dirty 
noisy place to work thats not the way it is anymore these 
factories look like science laboratories 
