<TEXT>
president bush and leaders of congress began 
negotiations today aimed at finding a way to break a political 
deadlock over next years federal deficit 
bush vice president dan quayle and top administration 
officials were joined by congressional leaders of both parties in 
the white house cabinet room they sat at a long table adorned with 
plates of pastries but answered no questions about where their 
talks would head 
earlier in the day house majority leader richard gephardt who 
heads democratic participants in the negotiations predicted the 
talks will fail if participants use them to seek political gains 
if everybody tries to politicize this nothing will be 
accomplished said gephardt dmo 
he spoke several hours before bush and congressional leaders 
were to begin negotiations over next years 12 trillion spending 
plan 
at the white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said that while 
president bush would not put forth any administration proposals at 
todays opening session well make proposals in later meetings 
fitzwater called the summit a feet on the floor and hands on 
the table session 
and reiterating administration assertions that nothing was off 
the bargaining table fitzwater told reporters no preconditions 
no preconditions no preconditions 
many democrats have said they want bush to lead the way in 
proposing any eletionyear taxes or spending cuts 
we have one goal gephardt said thats to do this as fast 
as we can and see if any good can result for the fiscal policy of 
this country 
the goal is to shrink next years federal deficit a task the 
administration says means coming up with 50 billion or more in 
savings fiscal 1991 begins oct 1 
stung by the tax and spend label president reagan attached 
to them in the 1980s democrats say they want bush to detail the 
size of the deficit problem and to lay out his suggested solutions 
they point out that in the 1991 budget he proposed in january he 
put the needed savings at 36 billion 
democrats promised monday that little will happen at the talks 
until the president describes why the problem has worsened they 
also demanded that bush help build congressional support by 
explaining to the public why unpopular painful measures may be 
necessary 
i want to hear what more do we need why do we need it and 
what are the choices the president will accept said rep william 
h gray iii dpa the no 3 house democrat and one of the 
negotiators failure to say those things will mean a deadlocked 
summit 
if those things are only said within the closed door of the 
summit i think that means a failure to put together a meaningful 
package because we wont be able to pass it gray said 
white house officials said bush had no plans to lay out his own 
ideas about reducing the deficit 
hell have general goals about getting the deficit down 
said white house spokesman marlin fitzwater 
republicans say they will focus on spending cuts as a way to 
reduce the budget gap they are particularly concerned about 
benefit programs referred to as entitlements such as medicare 
and federal employee retirement payments which account for about 
half of all federal spending each year 
they also want to tighten the budget law to ensure that any 
spending cuts end up as savings and are not simply transferred to 
other programs 
whatever we agree upon expenditure reductions entitlement 
reforms revenues you have to be able to say they wont be spent 
but they have to go as designed to deficit reduction said sen 
pete domenici of new mexico the ranking republican on the senate 
budget committee and one of the bargainers 
democrats will focus more on cutting the defense budget 
as for taxes members of both parties say they will wait for the 
other side to bring them up 
if there are going to be revenues theyll have to propose 
them said sen james sasser dtenn the senate budget 
committee chairman and another negotiator 
the talks were announced last week with both sides saying all 
options were negotiable this represented a departure from bushs 
1988 campaign pledge not to raise taxes 
democrats began worrying that they might be heading toward a 
trap however after white house chief of staff john sununu said 
last wednesday that the president would never seriously consider 
tax increases the white house quickly disavowed sununus comment 
but democratic feelings have remained bruised 
one administration official speaking on condition of anonymity 
said budget director richard darman would explain why the 
administration feels the deficit has taken a turn for the worse 
the reasons include the growing costs of the savings and loan 
industry bailout fears of higher interest rates and tax 
collections that have been lower than projected 
after that the official said opening statements and other 
preliminary remarks could last until next week there will be 21 
congressional negotiators and four administration bargainers not 
including bush 
administration officials and lawmakers have said the talks could 
last weeks or months 
the grammrudman budgetbalancing law requires a deficit of no 
more than 64 billion next year 
