<TEXT>
the farm credit system said tuesday its net 
income rose 85 percent in the first quarter reflecting the 
retirement of highercost debt and continued improvement in the 
quality of its loan portfolio 
the system said it earned 191 million in the three months ended 
march 31 compared with 176 million a year earlier 
the farm credit system is a nationwide network of 
federallychartered agricultural lending institutions that are 
cooperatively owned by their borrowers the system is the biggest 
lender to the nations farms 
the improvement in net income resulted in large part from the 
systems continuing efforts to enhance credit quality and to 
emphasize asset and liability management said james a brickley 
president and chief executive of the federal farm credit banks 
funding corp the systems financing arm 
the system said its net interest income rose to 321 million in 
the latest quarter from 239 million in the same period a year ago 
the rise stemmed mainly from the retirement of highercost debt 
that matured over the past year the system said 
in addition it said the improvement reflected higher credit 
quality of the loan portfolio reflected mainly by a reduction in 
nonaccrual loans to 251 billion on march 31 from 255 billion on 
dec 31 
loans placed on nonaccrual status are accounted for only as 
payments are made rather than when they are due 
</TEXT>
