<TEXT>
us agencies have announced the creation of a 
500 million aid pool to help promote sales by american business in 
the far east against governmentsubsidized competition from japan 
france and britain 
the money initially will go largely for loans to indonesia 
pakistan the philippines and thailand the us agency for 
international development said tuesday 
aid will provide 100 million of the money from its economic 
support fund most of which goes to israel and egypt 
the program will be limited to markets where other governments 
already are engaging in extensive tradedistorting tiedaid 
finance activities aid said in a statement 
tied aid typically requires a third world country to spend 
the aid on products made in the donor country tied aid usually 
takes the form of a loan at a low rate of interest subsidized by 
the donor government 
jeni falkiewicz of the us exportimport bank which also is 
contributing to the aid pool said the money would help businesses 
compete especially against tied aid provided by japan france and 
britain 
successive us governments have opposed tied aid because 
american businesses say its often prevents them from getting 
lucrative contracts overseas us negotiators have failed to win 
agreements outlawing tied aid though 
last week john d macomber president of the exportimport bank 
said he would try to get tied aid outlawed for some categories of 
products including power plants and communications system 
aid said the new pool will support projects in 
telecommunications transportation power and construction 
equipment projects helped by the pool will meet aid criteria and 
will be in line with the priorities of the recipient country aid 
said none of the money will come from its funds marked for 
development assistance 
aid has cooperated with the exim bank on some projects but the 
new pool is the first largescale effort of its kind its formation 
follows statements in congress suggesting that the united states 
reconsider its aid programs to take into account its impact on 
american businesses and jobs 
in addition to the 100 million from aid the exportimport bank 
will provide guarantees on 300 million worth of loans from private 
banks the guarantees enable banks to charge borrowing countries 
lower rates of interest 
the bank also will contribute 100 million from its tiedaid 
credit fund this is usually called the war chest used to 
match offers of tied aid from competing governments the bush 
administration has asked for another 114 million for this fund 
many members of congress would like to appropriate more one 
bill recently introduced would add 1 billion 
</TEXT>
