<TEXT>
two judges supervising hundreds of asbestos 
damage cases said they might seek to reopen the bankruptcy 
proceeding of the manville corp a newspaper reported 
the judges also suggested that the multibillion dollar trust set 
up by manville to compensate victims of asbestosrelated diseases 
had been mismanaged the new york times reported in wednesdays 
paper 
at a hearing tuesday federal district judge jack b weinstein 
and state supreme court justice helen e freedman ordered the 
manville personal injury settlement trust to explain why it had 
been depleted of cash so soon and why it recently decided that tens 
of thousands of asbestos victims many with fatal diseases would 
not be compensated until well beyond the year 2000 the newspaper 
said 
representatives for other asbestos companies named in lawsuits 
and lawyers for some plaintiffs have said that hundreds of millions 
of dollars were paid as fees to only a handful of plaintiffs 
lawyers helping to create the cash shortage the times said 
the two judges said they might seek to have the bankruptcy plan 
amended so manville which won protection from lawsuits in exchange 
for establishing the trust could lose that protection they also 
said the corporation might be forced to contribute more money to 
the trust 
in a veiled reference to the management of the trust the times 
said the judges reminded one of the trusts lawyers that they had 
the authority to seize the trusts assets and appoint a receiver 
as of march 31 the times said the 25 billion trust had 
received about 152000 claims it has made payments or promised to 
pay more than 935 million to settle 22204 claims the newspaper 
said 
lawyers involved in the manville bankruptcy and litigation said 
more than 200 million had been disbursed to fewer than three dozen 
lawyers who represent plaintiffs the times said 
last month trust lawyers filed bankruptcy papers saying that an 
asbestos plaintiff who filed a claim now would receive 40 percent 
of the claim in 2015 and the remaining 60 percent in 2020 payments 
would be without interest 
the judges gave the trust until june 1 to respond to their 
questions and hinted they would take action then the times said 
